## Mental Health: Evolution of the PHQ-8 score
Analysis of the distribution of depressive symptoms in the Italian population using the synthetic PHQ-8 score (scale 0-24).
```{r}
#| label: fig-phq8-rigorous
#| fig-height: 3.8
#| fig-align: center

# Rigorous calculation: mean, standard error, and 95% confidence intervals
res_phq8 <- svyby(~score_dep, ~year, survey_design, svymean, na.rm = TRUE) %>%
            mutate(low = score_dep - 1.96*se, high = score_dep + 1.96*se)

ggplot(res_phq8, aes(x = factor(year), y = score_dep, fill = factor(year))) +
  # Bars with transparency for aesthetic rigor
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 0.5, color = "black", alpha = 0.8) +
  # 95% confidence intervals (essential for rigor)
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = low, ymax = high), width = 0.15, size = 0.8) +
  # Labels with two decimal places
  geom_text(aes(label = sprintf("%.2f", score_dep)), vjust = -2.5, fontface = "bold") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#2c3e50", "#27ae60")) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, max(res_phq8$high) * 1.2)) +
  labs(title = "Average PHQ-8 score of the Italian population",
       subtitle = "Weighted estimates with 95% confidence intervals",
       x = "Year of survey", 
       y = "Mean PHQ-8 Score") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        legend.position = "none")
```
## Determinants of the waiver: Multivariate Analysis
The analysis using a weighted logistic model allows us to isolate the net effect of each predictor. The table shows Odds Ratio (OR): values above 1 indicate an increased probability of giving up care.
```{r}
#| label: regression-table
#| echo: false
#| message: false
#| warning: false

library(broom)
library(knitr)

# Model estimation with RIP as a factor
# We use 'as.factor(RIP)' to avoid the linear trend assumption
final_model <- svyglm(renunciation ~ score_dep + origin + year + as.factor(RIP), 
                      design = survey_design, 
                      family = quasibinomial())
# Cleaning and formatting results
results_table <- tidy(final_model, conf.int = TRUE, exponentiate = TRUE) %>%
  filter(term != "(Intercept)") %>%
  # Rename terms to make them readable in the table
  mutate(term = str_replace(term, "as.factor\\(RIP\\)2", "North-West"),
         term = str_replace(term, "as.factor\\(RIP\\)3", "Central"),
         term = str_replace(term, "as.factor\\(RIP\\)4", "South"),
         term = str_replace(term, "as.factor\\(RIP\\)5", "Islands"),
         term = str_replace(term, "score_dep", "PHQ-8 Score"),
         term = str_replace(term, "origineNati in Italia", "Ref: Born in Italy"), # R usually places the alphabetical category first
         term = str_replace(term, "origineNati all'Estero", "Born Abroad")) %>%
  select(term, estimate, conf.low, conf.high, p.value) %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), ~round(., 3)))
```
